post_text: August 24 is National Waffle Day. Pass the syrup! We’ll welcome any occasion to indulge in this iconic international treat. With so many varieties — Belgium, Hong Kong, stroopwafels, galettes – to enjoy in countless ways from adding classic toppings like butter and syrup, fruit, and chocolate, to waffle sandwiches and hotdog buns, we can’t wait to eat them at every meal.

post_text: In a miraculous stroke of culinary genius, someone thought that topping vanilla custard with a brittle crust of caramelized sugar would taste good. Of course they were wrong — it tasted incredibly delicious! The dessert is best known as Crème Brûlée (“burnt creme” in French) and depending on where you’re from, it’s also known as Crema Catalana and Trinity Burnt Creme. Whatever you like to call this intensely creamy, crunchy and luxurious dish, schedule your day of indulgence on July 27, National Crème Brûlée Day.

post_text:
National Hot Dog Day in July celebrates a summertime staple on a bun. Enjoy one piping hot and add some relish and mustard to go! One thing we want to know – is it a sandwich or not?
Celebrated every year during National Hot Dog Month, this day pays homage to the frankfurter, the footlong or wienie, wiener, wienerwurst or even red hot. They taste just as great no matter what we call it.

post_text: National Junk Food Day is celebrated every year on July 21. Dedicated to the foods we like to snack on, this isn’t your average cheat day. Today, you can eat junk food for every meal. Popularized in the U.S in the 1950s, junk foods are usually, by definition, high in fats, sugars, salt, and calories. But they are also high in deliciousness!

post_text: Without a doubt, National Lollipop Day on July 20 is a day that children of all ages can celebrate. We’re looking at you, grandparents — relive some childhood memories! People in the Midwest call lollipops suckers but they go by other names as well — lolly, or sticky pop. They come in many flavors but mostly fruit flavors for licking or biting. Lollipops are made of flavored sucrose, water, and corn syrup that are hardened on a stick.

National Peach Ice Cream Day on July 17th sweetens the day with a few scoops at the peak of peach season.
Since peaches begin peaking in July, this celebration comes just in time. It also lands right in the middle of National Ice Cream Month. So, it’s an excellent time to add peach ice cream to the growing list of flavors to choose from when it comes to frozen, creamy treats.

post_text:
National Corn Fritters Day on July 16th encourages us to fry up a batch of these crispy, flavorful bites of corn and batter! Make them with fresh corn and the celebration will be even better!

These bright crispy morsels make great additions to summer barbecues and backyard gatherings. The main ingredients include corn, meal, egg, milk, and butter. While they may have originated in the south, corn fritters can easily be changed up with peppers, onions, or herbs to give them regional and seasonal flair.

post_text: When it comes to snacking on something yummy, nothing can beat the classic macaroni and cheese, which is enjoyed by both children and adults alike. The dish has been around for a long time and has over the years evolved from coming out of a box to being packaged in a variety of ways with the condiments included. In America, the gooey baked dish is a favourite and they even have a day on which they celebrate it, which is known as National Mac and Cheese Day or National Macaroni and Cheese Day and marked on July 14 every year.

National French Fry Day on July 13th recognizes a staple food on menus across the country. It comes in so many different cuts and styles, there’s a favorite for everyone to enjoy!

French fries, also known as chips, fries, finger chips, or French-fried potatoes, are batons of deep-fried potatoes. No matter what we call them, they’re common fixtures at fast-food restaurants and are loved by all ages!

post_text:
Good Morning Warner Wildcat Families,

Yesterday, Governor Ducey made an announcement to delay the start of school until August 17th.

The LFAPA administration will be meeting to address this decision and discuss how to proceed. We appreciate your understanding as we navigate through this on-going, fluid situation together. The LFAPA administration will review the "Return to Learn" plan and will once again be put to the task of creating the best possible educational opportunities for your student(s) while keeping their health and safety at the forefront of every decision.

We ask for your continued patience as we once again face the challenges the COVID-19 pandemic has bestowed upon us all. We will remain transparent and will communicate the updated plan as soon it has been completed.

In the interim, if you have any questions please feel free to contact us.

post_text:
On June 24th, National Pralines Day honors a confection made from nuts (whether in whole pieces or ground) and sugar syrup. Pralines may also refer to any chocolate cookie containing the ground powder of nuts.

Around the world, candy makers create their pralines a little differently.

Belgian Pralines – contain a hard chocolate shell with a softer, sometimes liquid, filling.
French Pralines – a combination of almonds and caramelized sugar.
American Pralines – contain milk or cream and are softer and creamier, resembling fudge.

post_text: If veggies aren’t your favorite food already, National Eat Your Vegetables Day on June 17 is a great time to give them a try. After all, vegetables are very healthy. If you can manage a little experimentation in the kitchen, you can discover how many delicious recipes there are for them. So whether you’re digging into your favorite salad or trying kale for the first time, today is all about finishing the most colorful things on your plate.

post_text: The origins of Fudge Day are unknown, but it cannot be denied that celebrating this delicious, sweet treat is a great way to spend the day. Fudge is soft, smooth confectionary made by heating and mixing milk, butter and sugar. A variety of other ingredients can then be added to create assorted flavours of fudge. Some of the most popular flavours include chocolate and peanut butter.

post_text: Did you know that yesterday June 14th was Flag Day? In the United States, Flag Day is celebrated on June 14. It commemorates the adoption of the flag of the United States on June 14, 1777 by resolution of the Second Continental Congress.

post_text: On June 10th of 1943, Hungarian brothers Laszlo and Gyorgy Biro walked into a European patent office to declare ownership of their new writing pen design. From this day on, countless ballpoint pens have been enjoyed by writers around the world, and this date has grown into the holiday National Ballpoint Pen Day to celebrate the achievements of these ingenious brothers.

post_text:
Not My Arms Challenge
The Not My Arms Challenge is a great game to inspire teamwork.
For the Not My Arms challenge, two people have to pair up. Next, both of them have to put on a big t-shirt. The shirt will help you disguise whose arm we are seeing. Following this, the person in front will narrate what their arms are doing, and the person at the back has to act as the arms of the person in front when completing tasks such as eating, drinking, or putting on makeup.

post_text:
Dear Warner Wildcat Families,

I hope this finds you safe and healthy. I want you to know that we all miss you very much. I have come across a really fun activity that I wanted to share with you all. In the words of Dr. Seuss The more that you READ, the more things you will KNOW. The more that you LEARN, the more places you'll GO. Are you ready for a fun reading challenge? Are you ready to read here or there? Are you ready to read everywhere? I challenge you to check off as many as you can and email a picture of yourself reading in these various places to Ms. Malpass at kmalpass@lfapa.org, so she can post them on Facebook. Have fun reading and learning, we cannot wait to see the places and books you are reading. We hope to see you soon. Take care and stay healthy.

Ms. Chambers

post_text:
Hello Warner Wildcats,

I hope you are healthy and well. Service is a fun and rewarding way to keep you and the kids engaged while they are at home.

A few fun ideas are collecting food for your local food bank, clean up litter at your park, send thank you pictures and letters to service members, local resident nursing homes, and first responders, do some yard work for your neighbors. Here is a link for some more ideas.

https://kidworldcitizen.org/35-service-projects-for-kids/

Also, if you are running out of books to read at home, I like to read books through the Hoopla app or www.hoopladigital.com website. All you need is a Maricopa County public library card. With that you can check out books digitally for free. Google Books https://books.google.com/ is another free resource that requires just a computer or a phone. Another fun site is freerice.com. Kids can play educational games and the organization will donate rice to the World Food Programme. They can have fun and learn while doing a bit of service.

Take Care and I hope to see you soon!!

Mrs. Gummow

post_text:
Mrs. Mesa's Daily Challenges

Kids spend a lot of time and effort on their drawings. What happens, however, when they aren’t allowed to see what they are drawing?
For this challenge, you are going to need to give your child a pencil and a piece of paper. Next, each kid will wear a blindfold and then attempt to draw an object of their own choosing. To help the game go a little faster, you can have selected what objects the kids should draw, and you can set a time limit for everyone to submit their drawings.
Now, these challenges can be played in several ways. One way to play the blindfolded drawing challenge is for everyone to decide on who has the best drawing. Another way is for the other children – to guess what they have drawn. The first person to correctly guess the picture is the winner. Here is a look at how some other kids managed to do this challenge: https://youtu.be/U4qecKundmg
What You Need:
• Paper and pencil
• Blindfold
Have fun and don’t forget to send pics to kmalpass@lfapa.org!

Mrs. Mesa’s Daily Challenges!
Can you pick beans from a bowl with a Chopstick? This is exactly what the beans and Chopsticks challenge is about.
For this challenge, the participants will need an empty container, a plate or bowl is fine. Next, the participant will use chopsticks to transfer beans from a can or a bowl into the empty container. The contestant with the highest number of beans in the formerly empty bowl wins the challenge.
Watch these adorable kids take on the viral Beans and Chopsticks challenge:
https://youtu.be/DUzU3ASmttU
What You Need:
Can of beans
Chopsticks
Empty container
Please send video clips or pictures to kmalpass@lfapa.org

post_text:
Hi Warner Wildcats! 😊

During this time there is something I would like everyone to remember and that is to simply smile. What is happening is something no one could have predicted. Yes, we are all out of our routine and that can be scary. One thing I want everyone to try and do, students and families, is to find at least one positive thing each day. Just one thing that brings a smile to your face and joy to your heart. As a school, a community, and a country we are all in this together. I believe that by focusing on the positive things we can all get through this.
I am thinking of all of you and hoping to see everyone soon!
Miss Michalko

post_text:
Here is a recipe for Homemade Playdough from Mrs. Raub: I know parents are looking for something fun and hands-on to do with their children. Playdough is definitely a favorite in my classroom and at home with my own kids! Kindergarten students can also work on making letters, sightwords, and shapes we have learned with the playdough. Everyone else can get creative and create! Have fun!

Colored Playdough
Materials

1 cup water

1 tablespoon vegetable oil

1/2 cup salt

1 tablespoon cream of tartar

Food coloring

Saucepan

1 cup flour

Directions
1. Combine water, oil, salt, cream of tartar, and food coloring in a saucepan and heat until warm.
2. Remove from heat and add flour.
3. Stir, then knead until smooth. The cream of tartar makes this dough last 6 months or longer, so resist the temptation to omit this ingredient if you don't have it on hand.
4. Store this dough in an airtight container or a Ziploc freezer bag.

Calling all volunteers!
With our production of “Cinderella” right around the corner, we are looking for VOLUNTEERS to come and help make our show a success!
We will be having our PAINT DAY on Saturday March 28th from 10am—2pm in the gym. Bring messy clothes and your brushes. This will be our one big paint day, and an opportunity to acquire volunteer hours! Parents who put in volunteer hours will be given a select number of FREE RESERVED SEATS for their child’s production of “Cinderella” based on the number of hours worked.
PLEASE RESPOND TO THIS EMAIL ASAP IF YOU PLAN TO ATTEND!
Also, we are still accepting cash and gift card donations for supplies and costumes. A donation of $100 will get you 5 reserved seats the night of your child’s show!
We will be needing help with costumes and makeup during the run of our shows as well. Please call or email me if you are interested in volunteering in this way so that I can make up a schedule!

Thank you so much for your help in advance! We look forward to seeing you!

post_text:
Good Morning Warner Wildcats,

With the cold season’s arrival we would like to reiterate some of the dress code rules in place for outerwear. These rules and regulations are both in the enrollment packet and student agenda.

If your student(s) would like to wear a sweater in the building it must meet the following criteria:
• Zip up or button up solid sweater (no logos/characters/designs) in royal blue, navy blue, gray, black or white may be worn.
In respect to outer wear outside of the building, students can wear any color coat/sweater/jacket to and from school.

If your student(s) is wearing a sweater, in the building, that is out of dress code your student(s) teacher will send home a notification. More than one notification and your student(s) will be sent to the front office and a phone call will be made immediately.

If you have any further questions or concerns please feel free to call us.

Many thanks in advance for your cooperation and have a wonderful afternoon!
